  1. Do you think this sample was drawn from a normal distribution? Why or why not?

Answer: The sample has a ratio of intequatile range to standard deviation that is larger than 1.35. Hence it is not drwan from normal distribution. When we look at the qqplot and kernel density plot for a sample so small, it is a difficult predictor of normal distribution. If we look at the ratio of interquartile range to standard distribution, the value can be used to say if the distribution is normal. But we see the ratio found for a normal distribution of similar size, there is a small deviation from the 1.35 value.Hence for small sample sizes, the ratio is not always a good predictor of normal behaviour.

get_iqr = function (s){
q <- as.vector(quantile(s,probs=c(.25,.75)))
iqr <- q[2]-q[1]
return (iqr)
}

get_iqr(x)/sqrt(var(x))
## [1] 1.405773
#for a random sample
xnorm = rnorm(25)
get_iqr(xnorm)/sqrt(var(xnorm))
## [1] 0.9388596
#for binomial sample 
xbnom = rbinom(25,15,0.5)
get_iqr(xbnom)/sqrt(var(xbnom))
## [1] 1.057525
#for chi square
xchi = rchisq(25,2)
get_iqr(xchi)/sqrt(var(xchi))
## [1] 1.293445
d <- density(x)
d2 <- density(xbnom)
d3 <- density(xchi)
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(d,main="Random Sample 
     from 
     Gaussian Distribution")
plot(d2,main="Random Sample 
     from 
     Binomial Distribution")
plot(d3,main="Random Sample 
     from 
     Chi-Square Distribution")

  1. Now consider the transformed sample y produced by replacing each \(x_i\) with its natural logarithm. If x is stored in the vector x, then y can be computed by the following R command: Do you think that y was drawn from a normal distribution? Why or why not?
y <- c(log(x))
qqnorm(y)

y resembles a normal distribution more so than x. The ratio of square root of the variance of y to its interquartile range is also closer to 1.35 than in the case of x. It is seen that transformations on non normal samples can be normal

  1. Does this list of numbers have any interesting anomalies?
qqnorm(x)

plot(density(x))

Answer: We see that the density is left skewed. This is an anomaly since most natural phenomenons occur such that,the probability of larger numbers reduces slowly , unlike here where the probability of large scores occuring increases and then drops abruptly.

  1. Chris owns a laser pointer that is powered by two AAAA batteries. A pair of batteries will power the pointer for an average of 5 hours use, with a standard deviation of 30 minutes. Chris decides to take advantage of a sale and buys 20 2-packs of AAAA batteries. What is the probability that he will get to use his laser pointer for at least 105 hours before he needs to buy more batteries?

Answer: By CLT we know that the average of large iid’s follows the normal distribution.

#average pair lasts 5 hrs
mean_sample = 20 * 5 
# deviations 30 mins , 0.5 hr
var_sample = (0.5^2) * 20
sd_sample = sqrt(var_sample)
1-pnorm(105,mean_sample,sd_sample)
## [1] 0.01267366

  1. I want to and out the average number of people per household in the U.S. I survey a simple random sample of U.S. households and obtain the results displayed in the following table. Household size Number of households 1 27 2 34 3 16 4 13 5 6 6 3 7 1
  1. Lacking any other information, our best estimate for the population mean household size is the sample mean. What is the sample mean of our data?
# the number of people  per household results in only one person lives in 27 households, 2 people live in 34 households in the us and so on
sample = c(7,6,6,6,5,5,5,5,5,5,rep(4,13),rep(3,16),rep(2,34),rep(1,27))
hist(sample, breaks = seq(0,7,1))

#sample mean is the mean of the distribution
mean(sample)
## [1] 2.5
  1. What is our estimate for the standard deviation of household sizes?
sd(sample)
## [1] 1.410638
  1. What is the estimated standard error of the sample mean? (That is, based on our answer to (b), what is our estimate for the standard deviation of the distribution of the sample mean?)
#The sample mean deviates from the population mean by 1/sqrt(n)
#n is the number of households
n = 27 + 34 + 16 + 13 + 6 + 3 + 1
sdX_bar_n = sd(sample)/sqrt(100)
sdX_bar_n
## [1] 0.1410638
  1. Our error is the difference between the sample mean and the population mean. Using the normal distribution,find the approximate probability that the absolute value of the error in a survey of this form and size is less than 0.5
#error = population mean - sample mean
#find p_hat
zn = 0.5/(1.41/sqrt(100))
pnorm(3.54) - pnorm(-3.54)
## [1] 0.9995999
  1. Can we be reasonably sure that the average household size for all U.S. households is between 2 and 3?

Answer: Yes we can be sure that the sample mean that is 2.5 is correct and the average household size will be between 2 and 3 , since the probability that the deviation from this average (of around 0.5) is very close to 1, i.e 0.9995 or 99.95% ```
